1
00:00:05,104 --> 00:00:07,516
Mentioned in the Bhagavad-gītā:

2
00:00:07,516 --> 00:00:11,591
at the time of leaving this world,

3
00:00:11,591 --> 00:00:13,508
smaran bhāvaṁ.
[Bg: 8.6]

4
00:00:13,508 --> 00:00:17,111
Means what? You can say,

5
00:00:17,111 --> 00:00:21,804
it’s what you’re thinking of that time

6
00:00:21,804 --> 00:00:28,938
or it can also mean
the remembrance in the heart.

7
00:00:29,169 --> 00:00:32,236
[Final Heart Reflections]

8
00:00:32,236 --> 00:00:36,232
And there’s two schools of thought
about this, one is

9
00:00:36,232 --> 00:00:41,911
that literally what you’re thinking of
at the time of death …

10
00:00:41,911 --> 00:00:49,548
and then there’s the other notion that

11
00:00:52,085 --> 00:00:58,095
the cumulative effect
of life-long thought

12
00:00:58,095 --> 00:01:02,169
and remembrance and culture,

13
00:01:03,384 --> 00:01:10,892
and we would be more inclined
to accept that.

14
00:01:12,600 --> 00:01:18,740
Śrīla Prabhupād, he used to like
to quote this verse,

15
00:01:18,740 --> 00:01:23,879
I believe it’s from King Kulaśekhara,
where he says,

16
00:01:23,923 --> 00:01:28,084
kṛṣṇa tvadīya-pada-pańkaja-pañjarāntam

17
00:01:28,084 --> 00:01:31,835
adyaiva me viśatu mānasa-rāja-haḿsaḥ

18
00:01:31,835 --> 00:01:35,841
prāṇa-prayāṇa-samaye kapha-vāta-pittaiḥ

19
00:01:35,841 --> 00:01:40,825
kaṇṭhāvarodhana-vidhau smaraṇaḿ kutas te
[Mms: 33]

20
00:01:41,548 --> 00:01:44,452
He says, “Mānasa-rāja-haḿsaḥ”,

21
00:01:44,452 --> 00:01:47,728
which is 
an interesting concept;

22
00:01:47,913 --> 00:01:57,154
“May the swan of my mind
dive into the stem

23
00:01:57,154 --> 00:02:01,082
of the lotus 
of Your holy lotus feet”,

24
00:02:01,129 --> 00:02:02,483
something like that.

25
00:02:02,483 --> 00:02:04,854
Kṛṣṇa tvadīya-pada-pańkaja.

26
00:02:04,854 --> 00:02:09,403
Pańkaja means “the lotus”, 
pańkaja.

27
00:02:12,803 --> 00:02:20,170
It’s like the …
it’s taking its birth from the mud.

28
00:02:20,277 --> 00:02:22,037
A lotus has many
different names …

29
00:02:22,037 --> 00:02:24,831
ambuja, “sitting on the water”;

30
00:02:24,831 --> 00:02:29,044
padma; kamala …
There are many different words

31
00:02:29,044 --> 00:02:34,300
to indicate lotus, but …
So, there—

32
00:02:34,300 --> 00:02:37,720
kṛṣṇa tvadīya-pada-pańkaja-pañjarāntam

33
00:02:37,720 --> 00:02:41,390
adyaiva me viśatu mānasa-rāja-haḿsaḥ

34
00:02:41,390 --> 00:02:46,343
prāṇa-prayāṇa-samaye kapha-vāta-pittaiḥ—
[Mms: 33]

35
00:02:46,437 --> 00:02:49,731
saying, “It may be very difficult
to remember You

36
00:02:49,731 --> 00:02:52,192
upon leaving this world.”

37
00:02:52,192 --> 00:02:56,179
Because very often
that’s a condition where

38
00:02:56,179 --> 00:02:59,951
the kapha-pitta-vāyu
of the Āyurveda

39
00:02:59,951 --> 00:03:02,341
is all out of balance—

40
00:03:02,341 --> 00:03:04,036
the lungs are filling with mucus,

41
00:03:04,036 --> 00:03:06,540
whatever we’ve seen,
observed thus far,

42
00:03:06,540 --> 00:03:18,268
it’s very dislocating, 
imbalancing.

43
00:03:18,885 --> 00:03:20,846
So at that time
one’s got to have

44
00:03:20,846 --> 00:03:26,016
the presence of mind
to remember Kṛṣṇa

45
00:03:26,016 --> 00:03:29,443
in some profound way.

46
00:03:31,057 --> 00:03:34,915
King Kulaśekhara is saying,
“Maybe not”,

47
00:03:35,745 --> 00:03:40,471
or he’s even suggesting,
“Most likely, not.”

48
00:03:40,579 --> 00:03:42,784
So, what he’s saying
in this śloka,

49
00:03:42,784 --> 00:03:50,304
“Now, while I’m relatively healthy,

50
00:03:51,551 --> 00:03:54,963
let me … If I can remember
Your lotus feet now,

51
00:03:54,963 --> 00:03:56,590
that will be good.
Because at that time,

52
00:03:56,590 --> 00:03:59,762
I think it’s gonna be 
very difficult.”

53
00:04:00,717 --> 00:04:03,680
And there’s also a śloka
in the Īśopaniṣad,

54
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:09,108
something along the lines
where the devotee is praying,

55
00:04:10,923 --> 00:04:13,190
“It’s likely that
I may forget You,

56
00:04:13,190 --> 00:04:15,813
but You please 
don’t forget me.”

